STATUS

Investigated `MC-KANBAN-CREATE-20260627165916-74AF7F` — the "shining node not showing" complaint. Diagnostic complete; fix is small and clear; out of iterations to land the patch. Marking this card with the diagnosis and a draft fix so the next agent (or the next cron tick) can land the one-line change in seconds.

ROOT CAUSE

The shine effect (golden sprite + halo + cross flare) renders correctly — verified visually at `http://127.0.0.1:8767/memory-graph` by manually flying the camera to the latest node: bright golden star with 4-point cross flare and warm halo at the centre of the canvas. The Three.js node object (`__threeObj`) is correctly built (Group with halo SpriteMaterial + core SpriteMaterial, scale 72×72, additive blending), correctly attached, correctly in the scene tree, and the banner text correctly updates to `⭐ task:MC-KANBAN-CREATE-20260627…`.

The bug is: **`flyCameraToNode` does not fire on initial page load**, so the camera stays at the default origin view `(0,0,250)` looking at `(0,0,0)` while the latest node settles at world position roughly `(405, 1438, -76)` — which projects to NDC `(5.55, 15.64, 0.999)`, far outside the frustum. The star is rendered and exists, but is offscreen from the default camera. Camera history (probed at 200 ms intervals for 5 s after fresh load) shows zero movement.

Secondary finding (real but not the root cause of this symptom): `vendor/3d-force-graph/3d-force-graph.min.js` bundles its own Three.js (rev 160) which conflicts with the standalone `vendor/three/three.min.js` (rev 150-ish). Console shows 3× "Multiple instances of Three.js being imported" warnings. Doesn't break rendering in this test, but it's noise and a latent foot-gun — should be cleaned up by removing the standalone `vendor/three/three.min.js` script tag (line 243) so all `THREE.*` usage is on the instance 3d-force-graph uses internally.

WHY `flyCameraToNode` FAILS (best diagnosis from the code path)

In `setShiningNode(newId)` at `code/memory-graph.html` line ~447, the fly guard reads:
```js
if (newId && Graph && currentGraphInitialized) {
  flyCameraToNode(newId, previousShining ? 1100 : 1400);
}
```
On initial page load the sequence is: `initGraph()` → `wireShineBanner()` → `fetchGraph()` async → `applyFilters()` → `renderGraph()` → `Graph.graphData(...)` → `currentGraphInitialized = true` → `setShiningNode(latest)` → fly should fire. The flag should be true by then. Most likely cause: the rAF poll inside `flyCameraToNode` (lines 463–485) bails on the first attempt because `node.x` / `node.y` / `node.z` are still `undefined` when `setShiningNode` runs (the d3 simulation has just been re-heated but hasn't assigned positions yet). The rAF chain dies silently because line 466 returns without scheduling the next frame. The 3.5 s `setTimeout` safety net does run and calls `Graph.cameraPosition(...)` — but in practice by the time it fires, the camera has been re-aimed at origin by the still-running force layout, or the safety net fires before the node has finite coords and falls back to origin. Either way, the user lands at origin.

RECOMMENDED FIX (≤ 10 LOC)

In `code/memory-graph.html`, inside `flyCameraToNode` at the `tryFly` rAF chain (around line 466), do not return silently when coords aren't ready — keep polling. Also tighten the safety net to wait until coords are finite (up to ~6 s, not 3.5 s):

```js
const tryFly = () => {
  if (done) return;
  if (!Graph || !shiningNodeId || shiningNodeId !== nodeId) { raf = requestAnimationFrame(tryFly); return; }
  const node = Graph.graphData().nodes.find(n => n.id === nodeId);
  if (!node || !Number.isFinite(node.x)) { raf = requestAnimationFrame(tryFly); return; }
  // ...existing fly logic...
};
```
And in the safety net: `if (!Number.isFinite(node.x)) return;` (don't fall back to origin — keep polling until settled).

Also remove line 243 (`<script src="vendor/three/three.min.js"></script>`) to silence the multi-Three-instance warnings — `window.THREE` is already set by 3d-force-graph's bundle.

EVIDENCE COLLECTED

- `GET /api/memory-graph` → 200 OK, 895 nodes / 1126 edges (rendered view); latest eligible node = `task:MC-KANBAN-CREATE-20260627165916-74AF7F` (kind=`task`, created `2026-06-27T16:59:16`) — backend correct.
- `pickLatestNodeId` exclusion list `['entity', 'project', 'tool', 'session', 'file']` — correct; do not change.
- Banner DOM updates correctly (visible in screenshot: `⭐ Latest ⭐ task:MC-KANBAN-CREATE-20260627…`) — JS state correct.
- Scene traversal shows `__threeObj` Group with halo Sprite (scale 31.9, opacity 0.76) and core Sprite (scale 72.2) both visible and parented to scene.
- Manual `Graph.cameraPosition({x,y,z+90}, target, 1000)` → star renders perfectly centred (visual confirmed via screenshot).
- Camera position never moves on fresh load (5 s polled history is constant).
- Console: 3× "Multiple instances of Three.js being imported" — non-fatal but real.

RESULT

The fix is one small edit to `code/memory-graph.html` (`flyCameraToNode`'s `tryFly` rAF chain should keep polling instead of bailing when coords aren't ready, plus remove the standalone `vendor/three/three.min.js` script tag to deduplicate Three). I was unable to land the patch within the iteration budget. Patching this card to `blocked` with the above so the next dispatch can finish in <2 minutes.

